a</i>, itself probably of Brittonic origin, from any of a number of names beginning with <i>catu-</i> ‘battle’.","English: perhaps a nickname for a gentle or inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>cade</i> ‘young animal left by its mother and brought up by hand as a domestic pet’. In southern England, <i>cad</i> is found in dialects, meaning ‘youngest and smallest of a family of any kind’.","French (also <b>Cadé</b>): topographic name from <i>cade</i> ‘juniper’ (from Latin <i>catanus</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadd","meanings":["English: variant of   Cade  ."]},{"name":"Caddy","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Dorset): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Caddy</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Cada</i> (see   Cade  )."]},{"name":"Cadman","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>cade</i> ‘barrel used for herring or other fish’ + <i>man</i>, perhaps a metonymic occupational name denoting a maker of casks.","occupational name meaning ‘servant of a man named <i>Cade</i>’ (see   Cade  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":60,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Cade was born in 1322, in Devon, England as the son of Randolph Cadiho. He had at least 1 daughter with Miss de Dunsland."},"et":{"1322–":"1322–Surnud","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","about 1354":"umbes 1354","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1328":"1328","Dunsland, Devon, England":"Dunsland, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1322–":"1322–Kuollut","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","about 1354":"noin 1354","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1328":"1328","Dunsland, Devon, England":"Dunsland,